d interactions exemplifies to a rather nineteenth-century view of women. Sites and sources of change are also identified. In a global context where diversity is crucial to innovation, it challenges us to critically reflect on management and on higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducational leadershipxIreland. 0aEducational leadershipzIreland. 0aSex discrimination in educationxIrelandxIreland. 0aSex discrimination in educationzIreland. 0aWomen in higher educationxIreland. 0aWomen in higher educationzIreland. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aaccountability.  achange.  aelite.  agendered world.  ahigher education.  amanagement.  amarket.  apolicy.  astate.  auniversities.1 aO’Connor, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610309340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526103093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526103093/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles